            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "> Most of the time we don't need it. I think it is only for when the type name is hidden, as you say. I doubt that it that happens often, but it probably happen occasionally.\r\n\r\nInitially I thought that this C++ feature is only to be C-compatible but turns out that it has some use cases. The question is, does Cython actually allows those cases? I tried this:\r\n\r\n```cython\r\ncdef struct Grail:\r\n    int age\r\n    float volume\r\n\r\ncdef int Grail # error\r\n\r\ncdef take_grail(Grail g):\r\n    cdef int Grail\r\n    cdef Grail g2 # error\r\n    pass\r\n```\r\n\r\nand got errors. Not mentioning that this elaborated type specifier is not used for `class`-es, it means that even if there are real cases when Cython actually allows this name hiding, it won't work for `class`-es.\r\n\r\nI used workaround similar to what you suggested, generated full enum wrapper for a private name with an alias for a public one. Leaving it up to you to decide what to do with the issue, feel free to close it if you don't want to take any actions.",
